%N A395279 Jacobsthal's function H(n); the maximum, over all t having exactly n distinct prime divisors, of A048669(t).
%C A395279 There are several different functions referred to in the literature as "Jacobsthal's function", and the existing literature (unfortunately) uses a variety of notation for it.
%C A395279 j(n) is the maximal gap between all the positive integers relatively prime to n.  It is sequence A048669.
%C A395279 H(n), the sequence specified here, is the maximum of A048669(t) over all t having exactly n distinct prime factors.
%C A395279 h(n), the sequence of A048670, is A048669(A002110(n)).
%C A395279 It was conjectured (sometimes wrongly asserted) that H(n) = h(n) for all n >= 1.  However, in 2012 Hajdu and Saradha showed that H(24) = 236 != 234 = h(24) is the first counterexample.  The particular example achieving 236 given by Hajdu and Saradha is t = A002110(21)*73*89*101.
%C A395279 In 2019 Ziller computed more terms of H(n).
%H A395279 L. Hajdu and N. Saradha, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/S0025-5718-2012-02581-6">Disproof of a conjecture of Jacobsthal</a>, Mathematics of Computation 81 (2012), pp. 2461-2471.
%H A395279 M. Ziller, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1903.11973">New computational results on a conjecture of Jacobsthal</a>, ArXiv:1903.11973 [math.NT], March 28 2019.
%Y A395279 Cf. A048669, A048670, A062571.
